<p><em>Traditionally served with breakfast alongside fried or scrambled eggs, Gallo Pinto is a hearty and delicious traditional Costa Rican dish. It&rsquo;s a cinch&nbsp;to prepare, too!</em></p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" width="645" height="430" data-pin-nopin="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20645%20430'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="overhead of Gallo Pinto (Costa Rican rice and beans) in a red enameled cast iron skillet." class="wp-image-4380" data-lazy-srcset="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg 645w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-400x267.jpg 400w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-300x200.jpg 300w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-360x240.jpg 360w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-180x120.jpg 180w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-150x100.jpg 150w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-361x241.jpg 361w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 645px) 100vw, 645px" data-pin-media="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg"><noscript><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" width="645" height="430" data-pin-nopin="true" src="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg" alt="overhead of Gallo Pinto (Costa Rican rice and beans) in a red enameled cast iron skillet." class="wp-image-4380" srcset="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg 645w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-400x267.jpg 400w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-300x200.jpg 300w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-360x240.jpg 360w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-180x120.jpg 180w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-150x100.jpg 150w, https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895-361x241.jpg 361w" sizes="(max-width: 645px) 100vw, 645px" data-pin-media="https://stripedspatula.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/gallo-pinto-in-pan-e1442339841895.jpg"></noscript></figure>



<p>I&rsquo;ve always been interested in exploring international cuisine.</p>



<p>In addition to my trusty Time-Life <em>Foods of the World</em> cookbook series (which, I know I&rsquo;ve gushed about&nbsp;<a href="https://stripedspatula.com/grilled-shrimp-scampi/">before</a>; it&rsquo;s&nbsp;a vintage collection at this point, but if you have an opportunity to&nbsp;get your hands on a set, I highly recommend!), I&rsquo;m also lucky to have friends from a variety of cultural heritages.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/21433243352/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="black beans in bowl" title="Black beans | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5797/21433243352_9154164272_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5797/21433243352_9154164272_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5797/21433243352_9154164272_z.jpg" alt="black beans in bowl" title="Black beans | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5797/21433243352_9154164272_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p>Most recently, a few of my friends whose families hail from Costa Rica offered to teach me how to prepare some of their favorite traditional dishes, which, in turn, I&rsquo;m able to share with you (score!).</p>



<p>A few weeks ago, I learned to make&nbsp;<i>Gallo Pinto,</i>&nbsp;Costa Rican Rice and Beans. One bite,&nbsp;and&nbsp;it&rsquo;s safe to say that I have a new favorite rice dish in my recipe collection. I couldn&rsquo;t put my fork down!</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/21452703231/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="gallo pinto ingredients" title="Gallo Pinto ingredients | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/752/21452703231_8f810da99a_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/752/21452703231_8f810da99a_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/752/21452703231_8f810da99a_z.jpg" alt="gallo pinto ingredients" title="Gallo Pinto ingredients | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/752/21452703231_8f810da99a_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p>Gallo Pinto means, quite literally, &ldquo;Spotted Rooster&rdquo; in Spanish, characterizing the speckled appearance of the dark beans against the white rice.</p>



<p>It&rsquo;s typically served as a part of a hearty&nbsp;breakfast, alongside fried or scrambled eggs, with accompaniments such as sour cream (&ldquo;natilla&rdquo; in Costa Rica, which is thinner than the American variety), a crispy slice of fried white cheese (&ldquo;queso frito&rdquo;), plantains, sliced avocado, a corn tortilla, and a strong cup of coffee.</p>



<p>I loved the contrast of the egg&rsquo;s crispy edges and velvety yolk against the creamy, lightly-spiced rice and beans.</p>



<p>Plus, it&rsquo;s easy to make, especially if you prep the&nbsp;rice and beans ahead of time. (In fact, day-old rice is preferred, as the refrigerated grains are easier to separate and combine with the beans and sauce.) What a way to start the day!</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/21417975206/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="adding the rice to gallo pinto pan" title="Adding the rice | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/585/21417975206_c32d6bc88f_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/585/21417975206_c32d6bc88f_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/585/21417975206_c32d6bc88f_z.jpg" alt="adding the rice to gallo pinto pan" title="Adding the rice | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/585/21417975206_c32d6bc88f_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p>While&nbsp;Costa Rican cuisine&nbsp;is full of robust, fresh flavors, the heat level (at least,&nbsp;in&nbsp;the dishes I&rsquo;ve tasted) tends to be mild. If there&rsquo;s one thing we&rsquo;ve established on this blog it&rsquo;s that I&rsquo;m a total lightweight when it comes to &ldquo;hot&rdquo; spices, so I&rsquo;m pretty much in love!</p>



<p>The primary seasoning in traditional Gallo Pinto is <em><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/21452702731/in/dateposted-public/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Salsa Lizano</a></em>, a vegetable-based condiment&nbsp;used widely throughout Costa Rica. The sauce&nbsp;is thin-textured and easily pourable, with a golden, tan color. Tasted on its own, it&rsquo;s fairly salty, with a warm, round flavor of cumin and a bit of pepper.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/20823115133/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Adding the cilantro to gallo pinto" title="Adding the cilantro | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5796/20823115133_48f736870f_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5796/20823115133_48f736870f_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5796/20823115133_48f736870f_z.jpg" alt="Adding the cilantro to gallo pinto" title="Adding the cilantro | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5796/20823115133_48f736870f_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p>Many recipes suggest using Worcestershire Sauce as an alternative if Salsa Lizano is unavailable. &nbsp;I can see the general parallel, but Worcestershire most definitely lacks the smokiness&nbsp;of Lizano. For an authentic flavor, I don&rsquo;t recommend making the substitution.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/21452701061/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="gallo pinto in wooden bowl" title="Gallo pinto, served | Striped Spatula " data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/563/21452701061_1a716c34e6_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/563/21452701061_1a716c34e6_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/563/21452701061_1a716c34e6_z.jpg" alt="gallo pinto in wooden bowl" title="Gallo pinto, served | Striped Spatula " data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/563/21452701061_1a716c34e6_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p></p>



<p>I haven&rsquo;t visited&nbsp;Costa Rica myself (yet!), but from what I&rsquo;ve heard and read, it is an absolutely gorgeous&nbsp;country. The landscape is diverse (think: incredible beaches, majestic mountains, <a href="https://costa-rica-guide.com/nature/ecozones/cloud-forests/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">cloud forests</a>, volcanoes), the culture rich, and, judging by my friends, the people some&nbsp;of the warmest in the world.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/108879049@N08/20821519204/"><img decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%200%200'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="gallo pinto on plate with fried eggs" title="Served, with fried eggs | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/673/20821519204_c05f2cffae_z.jpg" data-lazy-src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/673/20821519204_c05f2cffae_z.jpg"><noscript><img decoding="async" src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/673/20821519204_c05f2cffae_z.jpg" alt="gallo pinto on plate with fried eggs" title="Served, with fried eggs | Striped Spatula" data-pin-media="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/673/20821519204_c05f2cffae_z.jpg"></noscript></a></figure>



<p>The Costa Rican people live by the mantra of &ldquo;Pura Vida,&rdquo; meaning &ldquo;Pure Life.&rdquo; &nbsp;It means living peacefully,&nbsp;positively, and in the moment,&nbsp;with happiness and gratitude for the good things in your life. Pura&nbsp;Vida reflects a profound appreciation for the simple beauty of life itself and the people in it. What a wonderful way to live.</p>



<p>I wish you all &ldquo;Pura Vida,&rdquo; including&nbsp;a delicious bowl of Gallo Pinto!<a name="recipejump"></a></p>


